pullRequest.body:
We add `fermatLastTheoremThree_of_three_dvd_only_c`: To prove `FermatLastTheoremFor 3`, we may assume that `¬ 3 ∣ a`, `¬ 3 ∣ b`, `a` and `b`
are coprime and `3 ∣ c`.

From the flt3 project in LFTCM2024.

This is rather confusing, as there is a `variable (hb : 3 ∣ b)` around. It would be much clearer if you remove the divisibility hypotheses from the `variable` line and add the ones that are needed to each of the lemmas.
Done.

There is a lot of repetition here with these three lemmas that all basically say the same thing.
It might help to work with `a^3 + b^3 + c^3 = 0` instead of `a^3 + b^3 = c^3`, to make the symmetry more apparent. Then the two further lemmas can be more easily reduced to the first.
Is this result used anywhere? If not, it can be removed, as it is subsumed by the stronger result `fermatLastTheoremThree_of_three_dvd_only_c` below.
Ops, I guess I used it somewhere in a previous version and then forget about it, I am removing it, thanks.
Again, the triple repetition of the proof certainly can be mostly avoided.
I've more or less avoided repetition, as you suggested. It's possible one can do better, but this seems reasonable to me.

Would it make sense to have a general lemma
```lean
lemma isCoprime_of_gcd_eq_one_of_FLT {n : ℕ} {a b c : ℤ} (Hgcd: Finset.gcd {a, b, c} id = 1)
    (HF : a ^ n + b ^ n + c ^ n = 0) :
    IsCoprime a b := ...
```
? I can imagine that this is likely to be used a number of times in the FLT project...
I've added it (it needs that one of the variable is different from `0`, I picked `b`).
Wait, maybe it doesn't need the assumption, let me see.
It doesn't, not the prettiest proof. I will have a look tomorrow or later today.
The proof is now better. If find amusing that we are missing `a ^ n ∣ b ^ n ↔ a ∣ b`.

what about [Nat.pow_dvd_pow_iff](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Nat/GCD/Basic.html#Nat.pow_dvd_pow_iff) and [Int.pow_dvd_pow_iff](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Int/GCD.html#Int.pow_dvd_pow_iff) ?
Ops, I somehow didn't find it. Let me use it to reduce imports, but I will also keep the version for integrally closed domains.

This block is still essentially repeated three times. I think it makes sense to extract one of the cases (say, `3 ∣ a`) as a separate lemma (with roughly the six lines above as its proof) and then use this helper lemma three times.
It was indeed possible to do the proof only once, thanks for the suggestion.

```suggestion
  rcases n.eq_zero_or_pos with rfl | hn
  · simp only [pow_zero, Int.reduceAdd, OfNat.ofNat_ne_zero] at HF
  refine isCoprime_of_prime_dvd  ?_ <| (fun p hp hpa hpb ↦ hp.not_dvd_one ?_)
  · rintro ⟨rfl, rfl⟩
    simp only [ne_eq, hn.ne', not_false_eq_true, zero_pow, add_zero, zero_add, pow_eq_zero_iff]
      at HF
    simp only [HF, Finset.mem_singleton, Finset.insert_eq_of_mem, Finset.gcd_singleton, id_eq,
      map_zero, zero_ne_one] at Hgcd
  · have hpc : p ∣ c := by
      refine (Int.pow_dvd_pow_iff hn).mp ?_
      rw [← Int.neg_eq_of_add_eq_zero HF, dvd_neg]
      exact dvd_add ((Int.pow_dvd_pow_iff hn).mpr hpa) ((Int.pow_dvd_pow_iff hn).mpr hpb)
    rw [← Hgcd]
    refine Finset.dvd_gcd_iff.mpr fun x hx ↦ ?_
    simp only [Finset.mem_insert, Finset.mem_singleton] at hx
    rcases hx with hx | hx | hx <;> simp only [id_eq, hx, hpa, hpb, hpc]
```
I think `n ≠ 0` is preferred over `0 < n` for assumptions.
I also prefer it, but I guess it's better to keep all the statements the same. Let me see how painful is to modify the `Int` and `Nat` versions.

```suggestion
  revert n; decide
```

is faster (`fin_cases` tends to be slow). In 3, we had `dec_trivial!`, which would do the `revert` automatically...

This can be stated for all exponents `n` and all integers `3` (and might be useful more generally).
It can then also be used to golf `isCoprime_of_gcd_eq_one_of_FLT`.
